      <div class="selfhelp-wrapper">
        <div class="selfhelp-header">
          <h2>Try This First — Free Liverpool Plumbing Fault Guide</h2>
          <p>These steps resolve around 30% of plumbing problems without needing a call-out.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="selfhelp-steps">
          <div class="selfhelp-step">
            <div class="selfhelp-num">1</div>
            <div>
              <strong>Find Your Stopcock</strong>
              <p>In most Liverpool properties it is under the kitchen sink, in a hallway cupboard or under the stairs. Victorian terraces often have it in the cellar or near the front door. Turn it clockwise to stop all water.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="selfhelp-step">
            <div class="selfhelp-num">2</div>
            <div>
              <strong>Check Your Boiler Pressure</strong>
              <p>If your boiler is showing a fault code or you have no hot water, check the pressure gauge on the front. It should read between 1 and 1.5 bar. If it is below 0.5 bar you can repressurise it using the filling loop.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="selfhelp-step">
            <div class="selfhelp-num">3</div>
            <div>
              <strong>Check Your Neighbours</strong>
              <p>If you have no water or heating, check whether your neighbours are affected. If they are, it is a network fault with United Utilities who cover Liverpool. Call 0345 672 3723 or visit unitedutilities.com.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="selfhelp-warning">
          <span style="font-size:1.2rem;">⚠</span>
          <p>If you smell gas at any point, stop immediately and call Gas Emergency on 0800 111 999. Do not attempt any checks yourself.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

